# LAMMPS Input File
# Licensed under CC BY 4.0
# A Set of Materials-Science Tutorials for the LAMMPS Simulation Package
# Tutorial 7: render the intrinsic stacking fault in fcc aluminum.
#
# A relaxed stacking fault has essentially no residual stress (its per-atom
# stress matches the bulk), so it is the LOCAL STRUCTURE that distinguishes it:
# common-neighbor analysis marks the two close-packed planes of the fault as
# hcp.  We color by structure type -- fcc bulk pale, hcp fault red, the free
# surfaces gray -- so the fault plane stands out.
# Open in LAMMPS-GUI and run, or:  lmp -in visualize.lmp

units metal
boundary p p s
atom_style atomic
variable a0 equal 4.08165
lattice fcc ${a0} orient x 1 -1 0 orient y 1 1 -2 orient z 1 1 1
region box block 0 6 0 6 0 8
create_box 1 box                       # type 1 = bulk fcc, 2 = fault hcp, 3 = surface
create_atoms 1 box
mass * 26.98
pair_style eam/alloy
pair_coeff * * ../Al_zhou.eam.alloy Al

# introduce the intrinsic stacking fault and relax perpendicular to it
region rup block INF INF INF INF 27.10 INF units box
group upper region rup
displace_atoms upper move 0.0 1.666 0.0 units box
fix frz all setforce 0.0 0.0 NULL
min_style cg
minimize 1.0e-8 1.0e-8 1000 10000

# CNA cutoff 3.48 Ang = midpoint of the 1st (2.89) and 2nd (4.08) fcc shells;
# cna = 1 fcc (bulk), 2 hcp (fault), 3 bcc (not present), 4 icosahedral not present) 5 other (free surfaces). use sequential color map to assign colors
compute cna all cna/atom 3.48
run 0

# horizontal (landscape) layout, atoms opaque, colored by structure type
write_dump all image stackfault.png c_cna type adiam 3.2 &
    view 85 10 up 0 1 0 zoom 2.2 size 900 650 shiny 0.15 fsaa yes ssao yes 4539 0.6 &
    box yes 0.02 axes no 0.0 0.0  &
    modify backcolor white boxcolor midnightblue &
    amap 1 5 sa 1.0 5 steelblue purple green red gray

